{
  "doc_id": "11039",
  "text": "Can identical ecological concepts be meaningfully applied to communities composed of bacterial groups from completely different phylogenetic lineages? Our review may in parts substantiate such doubts, e.g., with respect to the role of allochthonous [CITATION_1] or filament-forming (130) microorganisms in the two habitat types. Yet at the same time we illustrate that a focus on individual microbial populations also provides a platform to compare the ecological value of particular phenotypic traits, e.g., of motility and small cell size [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , or of specific growth strategies [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] in very different genotypes and assemblages across aquatic habitats.",
